1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:07,550 --> 00:00:08,350
Hi.

3
00:00:08,850 --> 00:00:10,120
Finally.

4
00:00:10,150 --> 00:00:11,680
Ozzak, dinner.

5
00:00:12,050 --> 00:00:12,850
About time.

6
00:00:13,720 --> 00:00:15,280
I was already heating up a can.

7
00:00:15,940 --> 00:00:17,840
Sorry, I had to close up on my own today.

8
00:00:18,120 --> 00:00:20,020
Marcelka's meeting up with classmates.

9
00:00:20,100 --> 00:00:20,580
Oh boy, oh boy.

10
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:21,280
So what is it?

11
00:00:22,050 --> 00:00:23,640
I'm hungry as a wolf.

12
00:00:23,750 --> 00:00:29,150
Beef in rosehip cream sauce with fresh herbs and bread dumplings.

13
00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:30,440
Yuck.

14
00:00:34,850 --> 00:00:40,450
Iva, can you please tell me why you make it when you know nobody here likes it?

15
00:00:40,950 --> 00:00:42,150
So I'm nobody, huh.

16
00:00:42,750 --> 00:00:45,250
Can't I sometimes make food that I like?

17
00:00:45,950 --> 00:00:47,050
Well, we had salad.

18
00:00:48,550 --> 00:00:51,450
Besides, there must be foods we all like.

19
00:00:51,750 --> 00:00:53,170
Like tomato sauce, right, bro.

20
00:00:53,170 --> 00:00:53,310
Yeah.

21
00:00:54,050 --> 00:00:55,450
No, I'm not eating it, I won't.

22
00:00:55,750 --> 00:01:01,450
I protest against dill sauce and demand that Ozzak and I be firmly warned about dill sauce in advance.

23
00:01:03,650 --> 00:01:04,850
You're already eating it?

24
00:01:05,850 --> 00:01:07,250
Well, now it's almost like tomato sauce.

25
00:01:39,170 --> 00:01:39,870
Thanks for dinner.

26
00:01:40,050 --> 00:01:41,910
Could we watch TV at your place today?

27
00:01:42,090 --> 00:01:42,610
Yeah, come on in.

28
00:01:43,870 --> 00:01:45,030
Is yours broken again?

29
00:01:45,450 --> 00:01:49,390
No, Lexa was trying to tune in foreign channels and now he can't find even ours.

30
00:01:50,970 --> 00:01:51,290
So what?

31
00:01:51,750 --> 00:01:53,250
Do you have anything to eat at home?

32
00:01:53,950 --> 00:01:55,050
Anything without dill?

33
00:01:55,650 --> 00:01:59,950
We had a wheel of cheese until end of the week, but mom took it to the neighbor's for steak tartare.

34
00:02:00,490 --> 00:02:01,950
Wait, so you haven't eaten anything at all?

35
00:02:02,450 --> 00:02:05,030
We looked at all the pictures in the cookbook, all the way to desserts.

36
00:02:06,950 --> 00:02:08,340
I'll heat up some dill sauce for you then.

37
00:02:08,340 --> 00:02:08,780
Yeah.

38
00:02:10,150 --> 00:02:11,350
Lexa, want some dill sauce?

39
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:13,280
I don't.

40
00:02:14,350 --> 00:02:15,750
Lexa won't have any.

41
00:02:15,850 --> 00:02:16,550
I will.

42
00:02:16,750 --> 00:02:20,550
Mom says food doesn't have to taste good, as long as it's warm.

43
00:02:20,550 --> 00:02:21,250
Here you go.

44
00:02:21,430 --> 00:02:22,610
Oh, thanks, Iva.

45
00:02:22,870 --> 00:02:24,130
Yeah, thanks.

46
00:02:24,210 --> 00:02:24,590
Wow.

47
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:26,610
Yeah, yum.

48
00:02:29,350 --> 00:02:30,650
It really is terribly hot.

49
00:02:31,450 --> 00:02:33,290
Their pace is reasonable.

50
00:02:33,290 --> 00:02:35,570
Their territory is the pedestrian crossing.

51
00:02:35,810 --> 00:02:38,090
Their weapon is the ticket book.

52
00:02:38,110 --> 00:02:39,030
They're here.

53
00:02:39,350 --> 00:02:40,690
Zebra Eleven.

54
00:02:40,690 --> 00:02:43,650
Finally they've started making proper TV series here too.

55
00:02:45,110 --> 00:02:46,610
This is absolutely unbearable.

56
00:02:46,610 --> 00:02:49,350
Tomorrow I'll have to cook something normal myself.

57
00:02:49,390 --> 00:02:51,650
You say that every time we have dill sauce.

58
00:02:51,890 --> 00:02:53,070
And this time I'll follow through.

59
00:02:53,650 --> 00:02:54,550
I'll bake a pizza.

60
00:02:54,830 --> 00:02:56,410
We all like pizza.

61
00:02:57,600 --> 00:02:58,680
A really big one.

62
00:02:59,240 --> 00:03:00,380
What's wrong with that?

63
00:03:00,400 --> 00:03:01,200
The bigger, the better.

64
00:03:01,420 --> 00:03:01,940
Right, bro.

65
00:03:02,450 --> 00:03:06,750
So big it definitely wouldn't fit in our oven.

66
00:03:07,750 --> 00:03:10,010
Well, I always exaggerate just a tiny bit.

67
00:03:10,350 --> 00:03:13,650
Hey, then how come I always find a pizzeria box in the trash?

68
00:03:20,550 --> 00:03:25,950
You'll meet the heroes of the series Lawlessness and Chaos again next week.

69
00:03:26,850 --> 00:03:27,760
Good God.

70
00:03:28,350 --> 00:03:29,150
What was that?

71
00:03:29,650 --> 00:03:31,750
The Czech version of Law and Order.

72
00:03:32,350 --> 00:03:33,350
It was awful.

73
00:03:34,350 --> 00:03:35,950
Even Inspector Rex is better.

74
00:03:37,780 --> 00:03:38,920
Good evening.

75
00:03:39,100 --> 00:03:39,560
Marcelka.

76
00:03:39,860 --> 00:03:40,480
Tomas.

77
00:03:41,750 --> 00:03:43,340
I have great news for you.

78
00:03:43,340 --> 00:03:44,140
Did you bring open-faced sandwiches?

79
00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:45,650
Something better.

80
00:03:46,150 --> 00:03:46,850
A little cake.

81
00:03:47,520 --> 00:03:49,280
I got you on TV.

82
00:03:50,070 --> 00:03:51,210
Berankova married Vlk.

83
00:03:52,540 --> 00:03:53,200
Who's that?

84
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:55,850
That host who does When Stars Cook.

85
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,240
Yeah, thanks, Marcelka, but I don't cook.

86
00:03:58,440 --> 00:03:59,260
You're cooking tomorrow.

87
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:03,760
Don't be overly modest, Tomas, I haven't eaten much from you, but you make excellent pizza.

88
00:04:03,940 --> 00:04:04,940
Those really big ones, right?

89
00:04:07,150 --> 00:04:12,650
Tomas, showing off your skills at the stove in front of the whole nation could really help you.

90
00:04:12,690 --> 00:04:14,210
Besides, I've already signed you up.

91
00:04:14,430 --> 00:04:15,610
Anyway, I have to run.

92
00:04:15,750 --> 00:04:18,410
We want to watch the Croatian version of Dashenka with Zoran.

93
00:04:18,570 --> 00:04:19,550
A wolfhound plays the lead.

94
00:04:32,750 --> 00:04:34,090
What are you going to make?

95
00:04:34,350 --> 00:04:35,570
I was thinking tomato sauce.

96
00:04:37,150 --> 00:04:38,250
Marcelka, could you help me a bit with it?

97
00:04:40,910 --> 00:04:42,010
I haven't made it in a while.

98
00:04:42,390 --> 00:04:43,590
But it's simple.

99
00:04:43,590 --> 00:04:49,850
You make a roux, add broth, cook it, toss in tomato paste, stir out the lumps, and finally gingerbread.

100
00:04:50,050 --> 00:04:50,750
Gingerbread?

101
00:04:51,250 --> 00:04:52,790
I wouldn't expect that in tomato sauce.

102
00:04:52,950 --> 00:04:54,350
My mom swore by it.

103
00:04:54,850 --> 00:04:57,150
And before she put it in, or after?

104
00:04:59,850 --> 00:05:00,530
It's not necessary.

105
00:05:00,650 --> 00:05:02,550
Just roux, broth, tomato paste.

106
00:05:02,590 --> 00:05:03,110
And you're done.

107
00:05:03,110 --> 00:05:07,630
So wait, I won't need this here then.

108
00:05:07,750 --> 00:05:11,650
Well, Tomas, you're going to strain it?

109
00:05:11,650 --> 00:05:16,550
Well, I was thinking something like squeeze it, you know, together.

110
00:05:17,050 --> 00:05:21,640
You'll manage on your own, I'm in a rush, mama is coming from Split.

111
00:05:22,050 --> 00:05:24,520
Well, then you'll finally have Zoran at home, right?

112
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:25,500
When his mother comes.

113
00:05:26,450 --> 00:05:28,040
Zoran can't stand his mother.

114
00:05:28,150 --> 00:05:32,620
He always promises he'll be home, and then sends a text from New York saying something came up.

115
00:05:32,620 --> 00:05:35,020
Then mama tells me the whole time it's my fault.

116
00:05:35,540 --> 00:05:36,320
See you tomorrow then.

117
00:05:40,550 --> 00:05:41,550
Wait!

118
00:05:42,050 --> 00:05:43,050
What's a roux?

119
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:01,340
Hey.

120
00:06:01,500 --> 00:06:02,220
Hey.

121
00:06:18,980 --> 00:06:19,740
What is that?

122
00:06:20,420 --> 00:06:20,900
A whisk.

123
00:06:21,140 --> 00:06:22,120
You wouldn't understand.

124
00:06:22,560 --> 00:06:23,040
I see.

125
00:06:23,950 --> 00:06:24,950
So it'll be tomato sauce.

126
00:06:25,380 --> 00:06:25,860
Tomato sauce.

127
00:06:26,950 --> 00:06:27,850
Or schnitzel.

128
00:06:30,850 --> 00:06:32,550
I also have beef tenderloin as backup.

129
00:06:35,050 --> 00:06:37,150
So I'm going out for a bit and...

130
00:06:38,250 --> 00:06:39,750
But I'll be back for dinner, okay?

131
00:06:39,890 --> 00:06:40,590
Sure.

132
00:07:03,750 --> 00:07:04,650
They were stuck.

133
00:07:05,250 --> 00:07:06,550
I had to pry them loose.

134
00:07:07,550 --> 00:07:10,050
Everything got foggy while I was kneading.

135
00:07:11,350 --> 00:07:13,050
I thought it was from the onions.

136
00:07:13,320 --> 00:07:15,900
No, it's all because of those stupid cookbooks.

137
00:07:16,100 --> 00:07:18,260
They're written in a completely incomprehensible way.

138
00:07:18,650 --> 00:07:20,120
Saute the onions until translucent.

139
00:07:20,120 --> 00:07:20,680
What?

140
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:22,840
Tomas, those are the basics.

141
00:07:22,840 --> 00:07:23,460
Or let it reduce.

142
00:07:23,640 --> 00:07:25,000
Where should I let it go?

143
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:26,420
How long is it supposed to walk?

144
00:07:26,580 --> 00:07:27,140
Tomas.

145
00:07:27,300 --> 00:07:27,940
Or a roux.

146
00:07:28,450 --> 00:07:29,650
What the hell is that?

147
00:07:29,690 --> 00:07:30,270
An animal?

148
00:07:30,390 --> 00:07:30,890
Tomas.

149
00:07:30,890 --> 00:07:33,130
Marcelka, I'm not going.

150
00:07:33,650 --> 00:07:36,250
But it can't be canceled, it's already in the schedules.

151
00:07:39,250 --> 00:07:42,450
Tomas, how many dishes can you actually cook?

152
00:07:42,650 --> 00:07:43,460
Three.

153
00:07:43,460 --> 00:07:43,680
Well.

154
00:07:44,450 --> 00:07:52,650
Cottage goulash, beef in its own juices, and Trencin sausage with beans.

155
00:07:53,850 --> 00:07:55,160
But I can handle stirring.

156
00:07:55,650 --> 00:07:58,220
For God's sake, why didn't you say so right away?

157
00:07:58,220 --> 00:07:59,800
You'll end up like Petr Kotvald.

158
00:08:00,950 --> 00:08:06,250
Last year, when his pressure cooker exploded, now every time he sings Geyser, everyone cracks up.

159
00:08:06,850 --> 00:08:08,050
What do we do?

160
00:08:09,250 --> 00:08:10,160
I have to go home.

161
00:08:10,450 --> 00:08:12,650
I'll be grinding meat all night for cevapcici.

162
00:08:13,350 --> 00:08:14,930
Anything for mama.

163
00:08:14,930 --> 00:08:21,350
If you want to inherit a steel mill in Trogir, you have to put in some effort.

164
00:08:21,950 --> 00:08:26,250
Marcelka, mama would love to see her daughter-in-law on TV, wouldn't she?

165
00:08:27,550 --> 00:08:32,250
Well, my sister-in-law Dragana was once on Good Morning Croatia.

166
00:08:32,950 --> 00:08:35,050
And since then I'm allowed to use the informal "you" with his mother on weekends.

167
00:08:37,150 --> 00:08:37,740
You'll see.

168
00:08:38,250 --> 00:08:41,240
And I could bring along a handy assistant.

169
00:08:41,240 --> 00:08:41,440
What?

170
00:08:42,350 --> 00:08:43,850
Excellent idea.

171
00:08:44,450 --> 00:08:46,120
You'll preserve your dignity.

172
00:08:46,350 --> 00:08:50,850
And when mama finds out I'll be on TV, maybe she'll stop calling me meatball.

173
00:08:51,850 --> 00:08:53,900
But you need to know the basics.

174
00:08:54,150 --> 00:08:54,650
Come on.

175
00:08:59,050 --> 00:09:00,170
It was around here somewhere.

176
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:04,150
It has a fork crossed with a mace on the cover.

177
00:09:04,370 --> 00:09:04,930
Here.

178
00:09:07,920 --> 00:09:10,040
Audio Cookbook of the Army of the Czech Republic?

179
00:09:10,480 --> 00:09:12,240
The fastest audio course on the market.

180
00:09:12,320 --> 00:09:14,320
Makes a chef out of anyone in two days.

181
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:17,350
In case of mobilization, in 20 minutes.

182
00:09:18,110 --> 00:09:20,710
Narrated by General Chef Otakar Glad.

183
00:09:21,250 --> 00:09:23,530
A recognized expert in quick meals.

184
00:09:23,850 --> 00:09:29,450
For home use, divide ingredient quantities by two and a half thousand.

185
00:09:30,350 --> 00:09:33,550
Army standards for beginners are calculated for a brigade.

186
00:09:34,750 --> 00:09:37,050
Wait, what's that sound?

187
00:09:37,750 --> 00:09:38,750
Something's chirping in my ear.

188
00:09:39,180 --> 00:09:40,000
Probably from thirst.

189
00:09:41,650 --> 00:09:43,350
Those are just my cicadas.

190
00:09:45,950 --> 00:09:47,350
Did she say cicadas?

191
00:09:47,550 --> 00:09:49,150
I know, it's chirping in my ear.

192
00:09:52,350 --> 00:09:54,150
Mama can't fall asleep without them.

193
00:09:54,550 --> 00:09:57,750
My, you're a perfect daughter-in-law.

194
00:09:57,950 --> 00:09:59,610
Mama must be thrilled with you.

195
00:09:59,610 --> 00:10:00,150
I wish.

196
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:02,700
I'll stick this on her window.

197
00:10:02,880 --> 00:10:05,000
She's always complained about having a view of Prague Castle.

198
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:06,360
And that's sand?

199
00:10:06,640 --> 00:10:07,660
For the bathtub and the shoes.

200
00:10:07,840 --> 00:10:08,620
She's used to it.

201
00:10:11,050 --> 00:10:11,740
Mamba, yours just escaped.

202
00:10:11,740 --> 00:10:12,020
Yeah.

203
00:10:23,430 --> 00:10:24,270
Man, bro.

204
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:24,590
Hm?

205
00:10:25,050 --> 00:10:26,750
Didn't know you were such a cook.

206
00:10:27,550 --> 00:10:27,950
Thanks.

207
00:10:28,900 --> 00:10:30,140
Is that charcoal?

208
00:10:32,350 --> 00:10:34,110
Hey, mind your own cicadas.

209
00:10:34,550 --> 00:10:35,750
Are they still in the shop?

210
00:10:35,830 --> 00:10:36,330
Yeah.

211
00:10:38,050 --> 00:10:40,260
Yeah, today they're showing When Stars Cook.

212
00:10:40,550 --> 00:10:41,640
And Uncle Sagvan will be on.

213
00:10:42,050 --> 00:10:43,500
So I can see what I'm getting into?

214
00:10:43,850 --> 00:10:45,760
Whatever Sagvan can do, I can too.

215
00:10:45,760 --> 00:10:46,440
Wow.

216
00:10:47,250 --> 00:10:47,750
Hey, look.

217
00:10:59,150 --> 00:11:08,550
And here's the guest of today's show When Stars Cook, player, rebel, and sex symbol of the '87-'88 season, Mr. Sagvan Tofi.

218
00:11:10,130 --> 00:11:11,390
Everyone with ketchup.

219
00:11:13,750 --> 00:11:16,350
See, I told you the strawberry is red.

220
00:11:17,250 --> 00:11:19,350
Yeah right, I thought it was yellow.

221
00:11:19,850 --> 00:11:22,150
On a color TV, food really looks different.

222
00:11:23,550 --> 00:11:25,450
And he's pretty good with that knife.

223
00:11:28,350 --> 00:11:34,670
Well, slicing onions isn't an easy task, especially when you're holding a cigar in the other hand.

224
00:11:34,670 --> 00:11:36,910
Hopefully we'll manage to stop the bleeding.

225
00:11:38,350 --> 00:11:42,750
And in the meantime, let's see how the duck is doing.

226
00:11:43,850 --> 00:11:44,750
I'm not going on there.

227
00:11:57,150 --> 00:11:59,350
You're going to let Ozzak carry on like this?

228
00:12:04,850 --> 00:12:07,950
For a while it was bearable, I felt like I was on vacation.

229
00:12:08,350 --> 00:12:10,410
Only stuff from Ozzak's collection can drown it out.

230
00:12:10,850 --> 00:12:12,110
Or Felix Holzmann.

231
00:12:12,750 --> 00:12:13,550
That's essential.

232
00:12:14,250 --> 00:12:16,050
We were catching them all morning.

233
00:12:16,550 --> 00:12:18,850
Ozzak got one Beatles anthology.

234
00:12:19,750 --> 00:12:20,650
Is that a mouse?

235
00:12:21,450 --> 00:12:25,850
Yeah, I told him they're not that furry.

236
00:12:27,050 --> 00:12:28,950
I'm curious how Ozzak plans to solve this.

237
00:12:28,950 --> 00:12:29,990
Ozzak already solved it.

238
00:12:30,950 --> 00:12:31,950
He went to the pub.

239
00:12:34,350 --> 00:12:35,150
What's wrong with mama?

240
00:12:35,950 --> 00:12:37,750
I put Valium in her tea.

241
00:12:39,150 --> 00:12:40,350
And I don't like doing it.

242
00:12:40,650 --> 00:12:43,250
She always confuses him with Slobodan Milosevic afterwards.

243
00:12:44,850 --> 00:12:46,650
I was worried something happened to her.

244
00:12:47,650 --> 00:12:48,420
And those clothes?

245
00:12:48,950 --> 00:12:51,730
It's the traditional outfit of a Croatian woman.

246
00:12:51,950 --> 00:12:55,170
When mama sees someone in normal clothes, she thinks they're a tourist.

247
00:12:55,650 --> 00:12:56,750
And she doesn't trust tourists.

248
00:12:57,550 --> 00:12:58,250
Not even you?

249
00:12:58,550 --> 00:13:03,050
Two years ago I wore a burgundy suit and she tried to sell me a carved donkey.

250
00:13:04,950 --> 00:13:07,060
But this year you're perfectly prepared, right?

251
00:13:07,250 --> 00:13:08,560
Not a chance.

252
00:13:08,560 --> 00:13:10,360
I heard her calling Zoran.

253
00:13:10,480 --> 00:13:12,040
She was scolding him for marrying a pale woman.

254
00:13:13,580 --> 00:13:14,760
I need to go to the tanning salon.

255
00:13:14,840 --> 00:13:15,280
Right now.

256
00:13:15,560 --> 00:13:16,900
Marcelka, wait.

257
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:17,840
What about the cooking?

258
00:13:18,250 --> 00:13:19,550
Didn't you watch it yesterday?

259
00:13:20,650 --> 00:13:22,350
We were pressing oil all evening.

260
00:13:23,050 --> 00:13:23,950
Sagvan was on.

261
00:13:24,450 --> 00:13:28,130
Yeah, I heard on the tram that he made a fool of himself.

262
00:13:28,650 --> 00:13:31,850
Well, he considered it more of an achievement.

263
00:13:35,650 --> 00:13:37,150
Don't worry, Tomas.

264
00:13:37,250 --> 00:13:39,950
Start with Glad and I'll join you.

265
00:13:48,250 --> 00:13:53,050
Go, you call that finely chopped, you beast?

266
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:57,840
Go, go, go, go.

267
00:14:10,950 --> 00:14:14,620
You should have been done ages ago, lives depend on those onions.

268
00:14:14,620 --> 00:14:15,920
Go, go, go, go.

269
00:14:15,980 --> 00:14:18,340
Go, go, go, go.

270
00:14:24,310 --> 00:14:24,750
Goulash?

271
00:14:26,020 --> 00:14:26,460
I don't know.

272
00:14:36,050 --> 00:14:37,370
Cicadas, you say?

273
00:14:37,550 --> 00:14:39,050
Yeah, something like crickets.

274
00:14:39,170 --> 00:14:40,210
But with speakers.

275
00:14:40,570 --> 00:14:41,010
Tons of them!

276
00:14:41,650 --> 00:14:43,690
Tell Tomas to buy some spray then.

277
00:14:44,590 --> 00:14:45,030
They don't stink.

278
00:14:45,390 --> 00:14:45,830
They scream!

279
00:14:47,650 --> 00:14:49,510
What about getting something that eats crickets?

280
00:14:49,850 --> 00:14:53,150
Then we'd have to get something that eats whatever eats crickets.

281
00:14:53,390 --> 00:14:54,990
My buddy Pekl tried that with flies.

282
00:14:54,990 --> 00:14:58,150
And those toads were crawling around in his curtains for another six months.

283
00:14:58,540 --> 00:14:59,540
Until a buzzard flew in.

284
00:15:00,850 --> 00:15:02,850
So how do you want to get rid of them?

285
00:15:04,750 --> 00:15:05,890
Crickets don't like cold.

286
00:15:05,890 --> 00:15:08,250
Sasa, please, don't get involved.

287
00:15:08,780 --> 00:15:09,760
What were you saying?

288
00:15:09,760 --> 00:15:16,020
The cricket played the fiddle all summer, unlike the ants who worked hard all summer long.

289
00:15:16,020 --> 00:15:17,500
Then in winter, the cricket suffers.

290
00:15:21,450 --> 00:15:25,600
Then the first snow whitened the day and the cricket fell, exhausted.

291
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:29,350
And snow gently falls on his fiddle, as he lies there stiff and still.

292
00:15:30,750 --> 00:15:33,880
A frozen cricket, I like that.

293
00:15:34,450 --> 00:15:36,650
Just wait until December and then open the door.

294
00:15:38,290 --> 00:15:40,530
Mommy, was there some bread in the basket, can I have it?

295
00:15:40,770 --> 00:15:42,670
Sasa, no, that was already moldy yesterday.

296
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:47,450
If it doesn't start freezing in two days, I'll go crazy.

297
00:15:48,010 --> 00:15:48,450
Wait.

298
00:15:49,150 --> 00:15:51,730
Horvath was offering me an AC unit for a pittance.

299
00:15:51,730 --> 00:15:53,670
I passed because it had "Post Office" written on it.

300
00:15:53,970 --> 00:15:55,050
I don't mind the label.

301
00:15:56,450 --> 00:15:57,650
But I don't have even a pittance.

302
00:15:58,450 --> 00:15:59,550
What if he'd take cash?

303
00:16:17,950 --> 00:16:19,350
Finally, come on.

304
00:16:19,550 --> 00:16:22,150
Marcelka, Glad was not a good idea.

305
00:16:22,150 --> 00:16:22,870
Take this.

306
00:16:23,750 --> 00:16:27,750
I chopped eight kilos of onions and he still demoted me.

307
00:16:28,350 --> 00:16:29,350
Are we alone here?

308
00:16:30,390 --> 00:16:30,930
We're not.

309
00:16:32,150 --> 00:16:32,650
Great.

310
00:16:37,310 --> 00:16:38,290
What happened?

311
00:16:38,630 --> 00:16:39,990
I sat down on the floor.

312
00:16:41,450 --> 00:16:42,690
Did something happen to you?

313
00:16:43,650 --> 00:16:49,470
I wanted to save time, so I was reading a dictionary of Croatian insults in the tanning booth.

314
00:16:49,470 --> 00:16:51,210
So I can understand what mama says to me.

315
00:16:51,850 --> 00:16:53,670
I didn't wear protective goggles.

316
00:16:53,950 --> 00:16:54,850
So what happened?

317
00:16:55,250 --> 00:16:58,950
Fuck your God, suck my dick, eat shit through a straw, Tomas.

318
00:16:59,250 --> 00:17:00,150
I can't see.

319
00:17:00,590 --> 00:17:01,190
Wait.

320
00:17:01,840 --> 00:17:03,360
Acute conjunctivitis.

321
00:17:03,360 --> 00:17:07,350
But by Thursday I should be able to see the outlines of larger objects.

322
00:17:07,410 --> 00:17:08,010
Hold on.

323
00:17:08,270 --> 00:17:13,880
You're blind?

324
00:17:13,880 --> 00:17:17,050
No, when there's light, I can tell.

325
00:17:18,650 --> 00:17:19,650
Then it's over.

326
00:17:20,250 --> 00:17:22,050
I can't cook alone with Glad.

327
00:17:22,050 --> 00:17:23,450
Tomas, Tomas, we'll manage.

328
00:17:23,650 --> 00:17:32,270
When I told mama I'd be on TV, she called Zoran and entrusted him with the first half of the family steel recipe.

329
00:17:32,270 --> 00:17:33,350
Suck it up, Dragana.

330
00:17:34,550 --> 00:17:35,150
Ouch!

331
00:17:49,150 --> 00:17:50,450
Good afternoon, Mr. Ozzak.

332
00:17:51,550 --> 00:17:52,650
Fancy a drink?

333
00:17:53,150 --> 00:17:55,750
Damn Croatian crickets.

334
00:17:56,850 --> 00:17:58,370
It's cold right here, actually.

335
00:17:58,550 --> 00:17:59,850
Nice chill, yeah.

336
00:18:01,050 --> 00:18:02,350
I'll go back and still nothing.

337
00:18:03,950 --> 00:18:06,150
The Croats are building a snow cannon this afternoon.

338
00:18:07,950 --> 00:18:09,250
Got anything to eat here?

339
00:18:10,150 --> 00:18:11,150
Just those bugs.

340
00:18:11,950 --> 00:18:14,350
In Sudan, they apparently make great crisps from them.

341
00:18:16,410 --> 00:18:17,090
Alright then.

342
00:18:18,750 --> 00:18:19,750
How about scrambled eggs?

343
00:18:19,850 --> 00:18:21,600
Scrambling is my forte.

344
00:18:21,850 --> 00:18:24,060
With something so banal, everyone will laugh at you.

345
00:18:24,250 --> 00:18:25,300
Well, we'll rename it then.

346
00:18:25,550 --> 00:18:29,480
We'll call it something fancy, like egg puree a la Paci.

347
00:18:29,480 --> 00:18:32,180
Remember what happened to Dalibor Janda on that Super Cooking Show.

348
00:18:32,280 --> 00:18:32,520
Right.

349
00:18:33,150 --> 00:18:40,150
He made ham and eggs, called it Blueberry Pork Mosaic with an Egg Target, and then spent ten years performing at country fairs.

350
00:18:44,540 --> 00:18:45,520
What's that banging?

351
00:18:45,660 --> 00:18:46,380
A slab of onion.

352
00:18:46,600 --> 00:18:48,280
Glad said it gives you strength before battle.

353
00:18:49,750 --> 00:18:50,890
Tomas, wait!

354
00:18:51,650 --> 00:18:52,550
Wait!

355
00:18:52,590 --> 00:18:54,810
You really have no experience with any food?

356
00:18:54,970 --> 00:18:56,830
Well, at Aunt Gerta's we used to make eintopf.

357
00:18:56,930 --> 00:18:57,470
Well, there you go.

358
00:18:57,830 --> 00:19:02,050
Whenever Ozzak and I carried out the latrine, we were allowed to help stir as a reward.

359
00:19:02,950 --> 00:19:04,150
Eintopf.

360
00:19:04,150 --> 00:19:06,070
German cuisine is all the rage worldwide.

361
00:19:06,070 --> 00:19:10,150
Zoran said at a Parisian restaurant he had pork stuffed with lard.

362
00:19:11,450 --> 00:19:13,150
I'll end up like Sagvan.

363
00:19:18,150 --> 00:19:19,210
Get the oil.

364
00:19:19,210 --> 00:19:19,810
Oil.

365
00:19:19,810 --> 00:19:20,290
Oil.

366
00:19:21,950 --> 00:19:26,050
Is there anything here called schmaltz?

367
00:19:26,220 --> 00:19:26,820
Never heard of it.

368
00:19:27,550 --> 00:19:29,250
Look at the label.

369
00:19:29,450 --> 00:19:34,630
Universal edible fat, made from petroleum, may contain trace amounts of hooves and hazelnuts.

370
00:19:34,630 --> 00:19:35,430
Perfect.

371
00:19:36,150 --> 00:19:37,050
We've got our oil.

372
00:19:45,740 --> 00:19:50,660
Happy cooking and good evening, friends of fine food and celebrities.

373
00:19:50,660 --> 00:19:59,050
I'm Petr Vlk, I'm hungry, and I welcome you to another episode of your favorite show, When Stars Cook.

374
00:20:00,350 --> 00:20:05,150
Today, former singer Tommy Paci will show us what he can do with a wooden spoon.

375
00:20:08,350 --> 00:20:13,550
And I can already see his family members sitting in the audience, so let me ask right away, where did you come from?

376
00:20:15,390 --> 00:20:15,810
From Prague.

377
00:20:15,890 --> 00:20:16,390
Great.

378
00:20:16,390 --> 00:20:20,450
And here's brother Franta, is that right, people call you Franta, don't they?

379
00:20:20,670 --> 00:20:21,090
No.

380
00:20:21,090 --> 00:20:25,870
You've got, as they say, quite a cold.

381
00:20:25,870 --> 00:20:27,710
What happened, care to tell us?

382
00:20:28,250 --> 00:20:29,650
I was exterminating cicadas.

383
00:20:35,050 --> 00:20:38,830
It's true they're a bit anti-social, but on the other hand...

384
00:20:38,830 --> 00:20:39,950
They sing beautifully.

385
00:20:39,950 --> 00:20:41,290
But too loud.

386
00:20:43,350 --> 00:20:44,950
Let me ask over here.

387
00:20:45,040 --> 00:20:46,280
Where did you come from?

388
00:20:46,280 --> 00:20:48,540
I see you have a basket full of apples, so probably from the countryside...

389
00:20:48,950 --> 00:20:50,240
Hey, you have to give those back.

390
00:20:50,350 --> 00:20:51,150
Oh, I see.

391
00:20:52,180 --> 00:20:52,760
Thank you.

392
00:20:52,760 --> 00:20:55,580
It's presumably some kind of family talisman.

393
00:20:55,580 --> 00:20:56,440
Ten kuna.

394
00:21:03,750 --> 00:21:08,850
Welcome Tommy Paci and his elegant assistant Marcelka.

395
00:21:17,050 --> 00:21:19,120
Tonight it'll be an international evening.

396
00:21:19,120 --> 00:21:19,700
Tommy.

397
00:21:20,650 --> 00:21:24,750
This is Hubert Essl, head chef of Hotel La Coupole.

398
00:21:28,850 --> 00:21:30,510
He'll be judging your dish.

399
00:21:30,750 --> 00:21:33,350
And Tommy, tell us what you'll be cooking today.

400
00:21:33,950 --> 00:21:36,090
I've decided on eintopf.

401
00:21:36,650 --> 00:21:37,550
What do you think?

402
00:21:37,650 --> 00:21:40,290
German cuisine is very popular these days.

403
00:21:40,650 --> 00:21:50,350
At the Ritz in London, I had an excellent sausage stroganoff with truffle headcheese on a bed of iceberg lettuce, naturally lightly digested, leicht Ekel, as they say.

404
00:21:50,350 --> 00:21:55,550
Mr. Essl, could this choice backfire on Tommy?

405
00:21:56,250 --> 00:22:01,150
In the hands of an amateur, German food can turn into a weapon of mass destruction.

406
00:22:01,650 --> 00:22:06,090
Let's hope it doesn't end up like the same slop Michal David produced when he attempted Italian, right?

407
00:22:06,090 --> 00:22:08,610
Ah yes, those notoriously bad ravioli.

408
00:22:10,150 --> 00:22:13,350
But now, the die is cast and we begin.

409
00:22:19,750 --> 00:22:21,350
Aren't there supposed to be labels here?

410
00:22:36,700 --> 00:22:40,300
Licking a spoonful of chili before starting to cook is a ritual of Mexican Indians.

411
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:43,340
In this gentleman's case, it's probably a cheap, how shall I say.

412
00:22:43,480 --> 00:22:46,820
However, if everything else works out, it might earn him a bonus point.

413
00:22:47,200 --> 00:22:49,780
Why should you be talking?

414
00:22:56,070 --> 00:22:58,130
Time is ticking, Mr. Pacovsky.

415
00:23:00,550 --> 00:23:01,250
You're not talking?

416
00:23:08,850 --> 00:23:11,650
Think, you beast.

417
00:23:12,150 --> 00:23:16,710
Go, go, go, go, lives depend on this.

418
00:23:16,710 --> 00:23:17,350
Move it!

419
00:24:03,350 --> 00:24:06,300
Welcome back to When Stars Cook.

420
00:24:08,150 --> 00:24:13,450
The food is ready, served, and we're waiting for the final verdict from Mr. Hubert Essl.

421
00:24:15,250 --> 00:24:35,050
Who would have thought that Dijon mustard with strawberry jam could create such an interesting flavor arc?

422
00:24:35,050 --> 00:24:38,950
And the finale?

423
00:24:39,850 --> 00:24:41,050
Deliberately, of course.

424
00:24:42,350 --> 00:24:45,250
Listen, my man, you're quite the little virtuoso.

425
00:24:45,450 --> 00:24:47,550
You didn't study under Escoffier, did you?

426
00:24:47,940 --> 00:24:49,000
No, not me.

427
00:24:54,650 --> 00:24:55,210
You should.

428
00:24:55,210 --> 00:24:56,390
You have enormous talent.

429
00:24:56,690 --> 00:24:57,570
Well, I don't know.

430
00:24:59,650 --> 00:25:05,550
But seriously, some bumpkin who can only appreciate tomato sauce with dumplings obviously can't appreciate such haute cuisine.

431
00:25:06,150 --> 00:25:08,550
But in the world, they'd be fighting over you.

432
00:25:08,750 --> 00:25:12,010
My dear man, promise me you'll start cooking.

433
00:25:12,250 --> 00:25:13,150
Yeah, absolutely.

434
00:25:13,250 --> 00:25:18,050
Wait, you really wouldn't criticize anything?

435
00:25:18,650 --> 00:25:19,450
Well...

436
00:25:19,650 --> 00:25:23,750
The task was main course, side dish, and dessert.

437
00:25:24,350 --> 00:25:34,850
However, after the chef's brother provided those exquisite Sudanese crisps, and that lady from the audience those beautiful apples at a reasonable price, I have no choice but to award full marks.

438
00:25:36,190 --> 00:25:36,910
Mama.

439
00:26:07,050 --> 00:26:08,350
So, what's it going to be tonight?

440
00:26:10,750 --> 00:26:12,650
Egg puree a la Paci.

441
00:26:13,750 --> 00:26:14,550
Bon appetit.

442
00:26:15,250 --> 00:26:16,320
Finally, a change.

443
00:26:16,650 --> 00:26:19,650
I was getting sick of your scrambled eggs.

444
00:26:36,680 --> 00:26:38,180
That's mothers for you.
